Higgs's box in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of Higgs boson caused a great shock last summer, and rightly.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is participate of the responsible mechanism of the mass of all that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what is more, it is the particle whose existence predicts the standard model: our better or "less bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for the physicists, it's not entirely clear that it's Higgs.
We know without a doubt that there is a new particle and that it looks a lot like the Higgs boson foretold by the standard model.
In addition, new data disclosed this week at an important physical congress held in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although there is still more data to be completely secure.
Anyway, let's assume that it's Higgs, because the chances of making mistakes seem small.
There is, in this great world, a generalized and unforgivable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to break that norm and don't try it too hard, because it will end up doing harm.
Although the physics of particles is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics in it: the principle of exclusion of Pauli, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantic state"; a "state" which consists, in a large way, of some of its characteristics.
The physicists classify the particles in two categories.
On the one hand, we meet with the good citizens called Fermiones, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And on the other hand, there are the boons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means that they can be found at the same place and at the same time.
According to the website The Parter Adventure of Berkeley Laboratories, which is, by the way, extraordinary, the boons are divided into two groups: the moons, of which we will not talk here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These boones, you could underline here, they're not the exotic kisses we could believe.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extremely banal boson: the photon or the "light particle" that acts as "messager" of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, "distorts" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a little like when we throw a stone at a pond.
In this "disorder" is born an electromagnetic wave (of light, infrareds, ultraviolets, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the boons "force carriers".
More stable fields
The same happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it's about another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" to make this boson appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it, it needs to reach extremely high energies, a little like a frozen pond in which only a thick rock could slide through the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN (the great hadron collisioner is a 27 km circumference ring!) to achieve such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles or all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do it, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never be kept by itself stuck to the door of a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do it have a mass, while the rest (as the photon, by the way), do not have it.
Now, what can all these investigations bring?, Mrs. Plamondon asks.
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between MS observations and predictions.
For their part, many eagerly want to meet, as the smaller difference could open a door to a "new physics" that covers certain holes in the model.
This, to say, still has enormous shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or the dark matter, which accounts for about 80% of the matter of the Universe (other ups!).
But we have not found such differences in the CERN so far.
Effects
The impact of such investigations in our day-to-day are difficult to predict, but we do not believe that we are wrong to say that there will be no one.
To see: In the early 1960s, laser pioneers in the laboratories did not at all suspect the revolution their work would cause.
They interviewed scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, as the physicist Willard Boyle, who worked in the Bell laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962, at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus".
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also come from all the tools around the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle developed a light capturer in 1969 during his research on optics.
Although it was not at all its original intention, this capturer now serves as "eye" for all the digital devices in the world, which was worth the Nobel physically in 2009.
That does not mean, of course, that LHC activities necessarily want to transform our lives, but that we never know...
