But in any exchange, a central authority controls and deals with the changes.
With the bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously depositors of accounting books, verifiers, coin issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses.
A user can choose a different direction for each payment, thus guaranteeing the anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoin changes are contained in the public account book, which is broadcast throughout the network.
The key hit is to write that new transaction in that book.
This is through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers and the winner, a type of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file sharing, i.e. the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique numerical trace.
Computers "cogen" the new transaction and add a number before "create" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular mark (more zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good.
The transaction is then indestructiblely linked to the chain of sets of other transactions; any change would change the mark.
If, in order to make a fraud, one user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would remain orphaned, as both have different tags.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided into two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to the hundred million, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in the calculation power.
