It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which gives it temporary full powers, he has decided to play it all over.
He took everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the Chief of State had given that Assembly two months more to finish his work.
And nearly two years ago, Egypt used a provisional text, several times modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial confusion.
This new initiative has only increased fractures in the country.
For his opponents, the president persevered in his "autocrat delirium" and continued "trading his word" and "putting the right".
On the part of its partners, it is ensured that it is a measure to end the institutional and political crisis more quickly and speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way of regaining popular and democratic legitimacy while debate causes damage throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote for him, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "or they vote my text or I hold the full powers", powers which are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, an Islamic majority, voted yesterday.
Most of the liberals did not go to the summons.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they believed that they could not make their views known.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, alternate members, were added to the room yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim brothers.
As we could expect, the voting articles have been unanimous.
The commentators are grateful, on the other hand, that one of the few differences in the day has been expressed practically at the time of prayer, so that a number of committee members came to think that the Constitutional clock was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted yesterday, contains 234 articles.
Article 2 of the Constitution of 1971, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia constitute the principal source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "the principles" could be replaced by "the rules", which would have allowed a more stringent application.
For Islamists, that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their good will and of their respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The liberals do it out of hypocrisy and consider it no more than a advertising craft.
According to them, Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University a consultative role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm its compliance with Sharia laws.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to pronounce are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we see the assumptions of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are further increased by the fact that the next director of the university would be much less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no specific religious involvement.
