Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of European Space Agency ministers last week, Poland was accepted as a twelfth member of the ESA. It is the second member of the ESA of the former Eastern Europe bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began to work closely with ESA in 1994 and participated in the Agency's project commission over the years.
However, the way from Poland to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts had already dedicated themselves to flying to space before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I recall, for example, the conference of A. Sternfeld in the astronomical observatory of Warsaw in which, on 6 December 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneer study "Introduction to Cosmonautica".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the independent assistants and, years later, Sternfeld remembered that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Sternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prize in France for his "Introduction to Cosmonautique".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned earlier, later became a major promoter of astronomy and cosmonautique.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautism, was known all over the world, and his contribution to science was rewarded when his name was placed on one of the hidden faces of the moon.
Already in 1925 a train was built in Poland that was to be provided with a rocket engine.
Regrettably, the author of the proposal is unknown and the project's scope is not known.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used for the start of the dress or for its brake.
Information on this dress is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
Starting in 1933, the Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to missiles.
The research was funded by the Techniki Uzarmjenia Komorka in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustavem Mokrzyckiegim.
Based on the preserved material, it is evident that the investigation has reached the stage of the practical tests.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by the Rohoziński engineer appeared in the specialized press, and the following year the study "Rakieta - torpeda voietrzna e rakitobomba a lotnicza" was published by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for the military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczysowy Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all missile projects for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polish Towarzystvo Astronautique).
In the November 1954 issue of Problem magazine, for the first time reference is made to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronautics.
In one of them, Professor Sototwicze proposed the creation of a society dedicated to cosmonautism.
Projects of artificial satellites had already been launched at that time and it was clear that cosmic research was a discipline with prospects for the future.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (PTA) has longed to be part of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the fall of that same year the PTA has become a full member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He performed this task until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the rocket probe RM (Meteorological Rakeita), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and was first launched on 10 October 1958.
The rocket had an apex of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg of weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed, and in the summer of 1959 air tests of RM-2 rockets began in two stages in the Błędów desert.
The rocket weighed 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of developing rocket would be the subject of a real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket would have an apex of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the wind of altitude.
However, work was suspended in 1962.
The successor of the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-step rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from one another through the space available to scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for the volume was 0.4 litres, in Meteor-1B 0.34 litres and in Meteor-1C 0.62 litres.
The maximum adage in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968 the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, the first of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km of height.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 version was subsequently built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland's entry into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined space space research on Soviet artificial satellites and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
